For the past three years, Taiwan is one of the most sought after countries to visit, because of its Visa-free policy for Filipinos. Aside from working out on a minimal budget there are plenty of photogenic spots for you to choose from. These are your options:

Taipei Main Station — the busiest railway and metro station in Taipei, Taiwan.

2. Longshan Temple — the most famous temple in Taiwan. During the 17th century, Fujian settlers built this temple as a gathering place.

3. National Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall — this popular tourist spot is a monument to a former President. It is in the vicinity of the Liberty Square and is adjacent to the National Theater and the National Concert Hall. No Taipei visit is complete without a visit to this memorial.

4. Taipei 101 — the tallest skyscraper in the world from 2004 to 2009, until the erection of the Burj Khalifa in Dubai which is now considered as the tallest building in the world. It has an observatory where you can view Taiwan.

5. Green Fantasy Forest — a fantasy-themed forest situated in Miaoli County. We took the bullet train to get there. It consists of various installations one can only see in fantasy scenes.

6. YehLiu Geopark — the home of some of the most eroded rock formations in the world. Due to rather soft limestone composition of the rock layers and the combination of seawater, wave and wind forces, this area is prone to erosion. This combination of factors resulted to a geological landscape that seems otherwordly.

7. Shifen Waterfall — this natural tourist attraction is a 40-meter tall waterfall that creates a rainbow as it splashes into the lake.

8. Jiufen Old Street — is a decommissioned gold mining mountain town, originally built by the Japanese and now a tourist spot where sky lanterns are released.

9. Houli Flower Farm — is known for the lovely flowers, plants and scenic farm.

10. Rainbow Village — is a former military dependents’ village that is colorfully painted by a veteran -Huan Yung Fu.

11. Grand Hotel Taipei — a 14-storey palace-like landmark located at Yuanshan. Since 1952, it has played host to many dignitaries who have visited Taipei.

12. National Palace Museum — is home to permanent collection of nearly 700,000 pieces of Chinese artifacts and artworks. Most of the collection are high quality pieces which encompasses items from neolithic age to the modern period.

How I miss traveling? I wish I could do it again soon.

I have booked tickets for Lakbay Museo through the Klook App. I have always been fond of traveling the peninsula and experience the variant culture this country has to offer. I was wondering how can I travel and experience the different regions without having to leave Manila? Back in the days, when we go on field trips, we used to go to Nayong Pilipino where we get to know the various culture of the different regions in the country.

Lakbay Museo is a very colorful place. Just like the Philippines, it offers unique experiences in various destinations. It lets you travel to Luzon, Visayas and Mindanao and get to know more about the history of the Philippines and the rich culture of specific regions.

Lakbay Museo is located at S Maison in Conrad Manila at the Mall of Asia Complex.

There are three ways to enter the museum: through the jeepney on the left, the airplane on the center or the vinta (partially hidden in the picture). So one can travel to the different parts of the country through land, air and water.

Luzon

When you enter the museum, you will immediately see the market and the various produce the region has to offer.

Luzon has attractive traditional houses which we can easily relate because we grew up in this kind of setting.

The different produce and cuisine Luzon has to offer.

The colorful celebrations and festivals being celebrated in Luzon.

The historical landmark — Barasoain Church where the inauguration of First Republic of the Philippines was held.

The miniature display of the Mayon Volcano, famous for its perfect cone appearance, and I posed beside the ruins of Cagsawa Church.

Visayas

The Visayas region is known for its famous beaches and under the sea adventures.

Mindanao

The different displays depict the island’s dances, musical instruments and grandeur wood carvings and vintas.

There are also cultural performances which include traditional dances and with full-blown production.

I enjoyed visiting Lakbay Museo. It helped me rediscover the passion to travel and learn from the different cultures that the Philippines has to offer. I appreciated the time that I can experience the various places in the country through an interactive museum.

LAKBAY MUSEO

Level 1, S Maison, Marina Way, Mall of Asia Complex

Pasay City, Philippines

After two years of pandemic, this Holy Week 2022, is observed with special solemnity as a time for devotion by the Catholic faithful. It has been a tradition for Filipinos to practice Visita Iglesia during Maundy Thursday.

Visita Iglesia is the practice of visiting seven different churches, especially during Maundy Thursday. Filipino families travel to visit these churches to fulfill their sacred mission and to have family bonding as well.

The churches we visited were:

San Andres Apostol Parish (Greenwoods Executive Village, Cainta)

Since 1990, the Greenwoods Executive Village Homeowner’s Association adopted San Andres Apostol as the patron saint. Because the location of the church is situated within the vicinity of Barangay San Andres Cainta Rizal. The masses were initiated by the first dwellers of the village and invited priests to celebrate masses with them.

The ground breaking ceremony was held on December 14, 2008. For years, the now erected church was named the new San Andres Apostol Parish.

San Andres (St. Andrew), though the least spoken apostle in the Bible, was indeed the perfect choice to be hand-picked by the parishioners to become their patron. As called by Jesus to be one of the “Fishers of Men”, the patron seems to never rest on calling the Greenwoods residents and nearby residents to be the “present fishermen” in the area. San Andres Apostol Parish may be a very young parish, but you will be surprised by its growth. And the parishioners, guided by their parish priest with the intercession of their patron, believe that their journey is just beginning.

2. Sta. Clara de Montefalco Parish (C. Raymundo Ave., Caniogan, Pasig)

It is considered the tallest church in the Philippines. Currently standing at 57 meters tall on 11,230 square meters of land, situated along C. Raymundo Ave., Brgy. Caniogan, Pasig City.

The chapel which was originally placed along Dr. Sixto Antonio Ave., has been recognized as a historical site by the National Historical Institute. An earthquake in 1880, led to the construction of this new church.

The Sta. Clara de Montefalco’s dome, patterned after the majestic dome of St. Peter’s Basilica in Vatican City, greets visitors from less than a kilometer away.

A semi-circular ramp welcomes visitors to the church lobby. Two staircases in the front will also lead into the lobby.

The hall has two floors: the ground floor, which can seat up to 2,000 people; and the balcony, which extends to the left and right sides of the church, with open space that can accommodate about another 500 people. Twenty tall windows, with clear glass panes, decorated with stained glass, each window depicting a mystery of the Holy Rosary.

The magnificent altar is adorned with intricate carvings themed after the coconut tree (the tree of life), and figures of the Crucifix, St. Joseph, the Immaculate Conception, and the parish’s patron saint, Sta. Clara de Montefalco in the center. Two minor retablos (devotional painting derived from traditional Catholic church art) are constructed on both sides of the main altar. The church also has a seven-story rectory at the back, which 16 rooms for the use of priests.

3. Sta. Rosa De Lima Parish (San Buenaventura Drive, Bagong Ilog, Pasig)

Situated at San Buenaventura Drive, Brgy. Bagong Ilog in Pasig City. The church’s patroness was the image of Santa Rosa de Lima, a saint that is revered by the area as miraculous.

Do you know that they celebrate their feast once in every two years? So Brgy. Sumilang and Brgy. Bagong Ilog share this event every other year.

Her discovery was shrouded with mystery where one day, two friends who are both fishermen, one from Sumilang (Celestino Cruz) and another from Bagong Ilog (Ubaldo Intalan) visited a beautiful girl in Mandaluyong. Going there, they tried avoiding the cave as they heard frightening stories about the place. However, they had to gather fire wood on their way back. This is the reason why they decided to go near the cave where wood was plentiful and just scattered around.

While doing so, they were surprised to smell a very fragrant scent all over the place, seemingly from a dama de noche (night-blooming jasmine) flower. They started searching where the scent was coming from. They were astounded to see emerging lights from inside the cave and decided to go inside it. Astoundingly, they saw a very beautiful image which they didn’t recognize at first. Similar to a pirate who found a chest full of gold and diamonds, the two friends immediately and happily brought their newfound discovery to Bagong Ilog. There, they found out that the image was Sta. Rosa of Lima, Peru. It is believed that through the guidance of the Lord Jesus Christ, he has led Sta. Rosa de Lima to be discovered by the fishermen to guide the people of both barangays.

4. National Shrine of Our Lady of Guadalupe (Orense St., Guadalupe Nuevo, Makati)

When I was a baby, I was baptized here because we stayed in this place as an infant. The National Shrine of Our Lady of Guadalupe is located at 1923 Orense Street, Guadalupe, Nuevo, Makati City. It is under the jurisdiction of the Archdiocese of Manila.

The Church was established in the 17th century and, at first, named Our Lady of Grace Church. It was only in the year 1803 when its name was changed to Our Lady of Guadalupe.

In the year 2002, it was declared an Archdiocesan Shrine, and in the year 2010, declared a National Shrine. The shrine houses the miraculous image of Our Lady of Guadalupe, the patroness of the pro-life movement and the secondary patroness of the Philippines.

5. Santuario de San Antonio Parish (McKinley Road, Forbes Park, Makati)

In the upscale Forbes Park in Makati, rests Santuario de San Antonio. It was built at the end of World War II by the Franciscans, after their mother church in Intramuros was destroyed. The friars dedicated the church, the santuario, or the sanctuary to Saint Anthony and brought an old statue of the saint from their old church.

The decades-old church features cross-shaped layout with a dome-shaped ceiling. Moreover, displayed on its walls are paintings done by Italian artist Giotto and Philippines’ first national artist, Fernando Amorsolo.

Santuario de San Antonio is a popular venue not only due to its weekly masses, but also due to it being one of the top choices for couples, especially those who belong to influential and rich families, who prefer a Catholic wedding.

To this day, the Catholic brethren of Santuario de San Antonio continue to inspire people to grow in their faith. It remains as a prominent landmark to Forbes Park residents and those who live nearby.

6. St. Alphonsus Mary de Liguori Parish (Lapu-Lapu St., Magallanes, Makati)

Going round in circles, along Magallanes and Dasmariñas Village in Makati, we have found this church in the corners of Lapu-Lapu and Humabon Streets in Brgy. Magallanes.

In 1968, Architect Leandro Locsin designed an 800-square-meter parish church that was intimate and low, with an interior that was dark. The plan was a perfect square, 28 meters each side, with a four-meter-high ceiling that was flat. The central aisle ran along the diagonal of the square. Marching along the perimeter were 28 four-meter tall concrete buttresses, which were wide at the base and narrow at the top. They seemed to support a massive roof slab, which was actually a tall parapet wall that shielded the corrugated metal roof.

When fire destroyed the building, in September 2004, only the 28 buttresses remained. After much deliberation, the parish decided that it would be more economical and symbolically pithy to salvage the buttresses, rather than demolish them and start from scratch. The 28 buttresses, originally designed for aesthetic effect, were hollow. It is now filled with concrete to fulfill a new structural purpose of providing lateral support to the new composite columns that carry the roof vaults.

6. Archdiocesan Shrine of Jesus, the Way, the Truth and the Life (Coral Way, Brgy. 76, Pasay)

The church is located along Coral Way within the SM Mall of Asia Complex in Pasay.

The dream of building a church in this vast property was inspired by the visit of the late Pope John Paul II in the Philippines. When the late Pope John Paul II visited the Philippines in 1995 for the World Youth Day, he envisioned a shrine for Jesus. The Archdiocesan Shrine of Jesus, the Way, the Truth and the Life is then the fulfillment of that dream. The project was spearheaded by the then Archbishop of Manila, the late Jaime L. Cardinal Sin, DD. His love for the youth, which he shared with the Holy Father, urged him to push for the construction of the Shrine of Jesus. But it was the benevolent hearts of Shoe Mart Group of Companies’ founders, Mr. and Mrs. Henry Sy Jr. that has lead the Archbishop’s dreams to materialize.

Beneath the church is a function hall that can be used for wedding receptions called Pope John Paul Youth Center, Shrine of Jesus Hall.

You will never believe how happy we were to experience all of these again after two years of community lockdowns.

Until next time…

#grateful #garensfamilytravels2022 #Apr142022

Kath

I have never gone to Cebu before but I have been hearing a lot of things about it. For one, it is one of the most favoured destinations in my country — Philippines. This urban city is known to be rich in history for it was the birthplace of Christianity in Asia.

Outside of the Metro, there are gorgeous beaches that you can bask in. There are majestic waterfalls and nature paths that you can revel in. There are big festivals and local cuisines you can indulge in… and there are so much more! This intrigued me to explore the city.

My travel to this island would not be possible without the help of people to whom I have interacted with for just a moment in the conference that I have attended.

Before we prepared for our trip, my family and I first indulged in a breakfast buffet at our hotel.

We started our day trip to the beautiful Sirao Flower Garden. There are two gardens here but the more picturesque of the two is the one with the artificial windmill so we opted to enter it.

Entrance Fee: Php 50.00 on January 1, 2019 but it will be Php 100.00/person.

Everything is lovely. It is ready to attract more tourists in the future as its staff continuously doing the efforts to improve the place.

Next stop is the Temple of Leah which was constructed in 2012. The significance of this place is that it was built as a metaphor for a husband’s undying love and devotion to his deceased wife. You heard it right, it is similar to the story of the Taj Mahal — a UNESCO World Heritage site which is an immense mausoleum built in India.

Entrance Fee: Php 50.00/person.

In this seven-storey shrine, you can see gigantic lions guarding its doorsteps. It is a mixture of Greek and Roman mythology inspired architecture where one can really appreciate its masterpiece.

Of course, we would also want to visit the Taoist Temple. It was built in 1972 by the Chinese community residing in Cebu. The temple includes the chapel, library, souvenir shop and the wishing well. You can view the entire city when you stay in the spacious balcony.

We also proceeded to the historical site where it holds a big part of the history of Cebu. The Magellan’s Cross was planted upon the arrival of Spanish and Portuguese explorers led by the infamous discoverer — Ferdinand Magellan on March 15, 1521.

Among other tourist attractions we have chosen Fort San Pedro as our last historical destination for the day. It is the smallest and oldest military defence structure in the country.

This bastion is also the embryo of the first Spanish settlement here in the country.

Other sites that we took photos of are:

Cebu City Hall

Plaza Independencia

Sto. Niño Parochial School

But our trip would not be complete without tasting the sumptuous Lechon Cebu.

There are so many places to go to for such a little time. I wish someday, I will be able to visit the outskirts of Cebu and enjoy nature at its finest.

Kath

When you talk about dessert, it means a course usually sweet taken after a meal. Most people, would be the sweet tooth – one wouldn’t resist some sugar rush.

Well, I’m not much of a dessert person because I don’t have the “sweet tooth” in me. I’m more of a “go to experience the fad” person, so whatever is new, I usually grab the opportunity to be with my family and appreciate the time to be with them.

Another Instagram haven in this side of Manila is The Dessert Museum. It is not your typical museum because you’ll experience the setting of eight mouthwatering rooms of sugar-filled happiness. This sweet wonderland was launched only this year last February at the posh address – S’ Maison inside Conrad Hotel Manila.

True to their claim, you’ll get enticed to these rooms with their guides that will share information about each of the rooms. My children even suggested that I should have a Top 8 of the most favored rooms for us. Eight being the least favorite and one being the most favorite. So here’s the order of my Top 8 rooms in The Dessert Museum.

8 : Gummy Bears

I wasn’t able to enjoy this themed room because I wasn’t able to receive any treat.

There are miniature gummy bears stuck on the wall. Four giant gummy bears on the side, small bath tubs filled with balls and a trampoline one can jump on.

7: Gumball Room

My kids went inside a giant gumball machine. The airflow and flying balloons add impact to the pictures I’ve taken.

6: Donut Room

The entrance to the museum is a slide through a humongous donut hole and into the donut room, or you can descend the stairs.

And here’s a treat from this room…

5: Cake Pops

Giant cake pops are suspended upside down, and one can sit on it but it’s too hard to get on it.

With the dress I wore on that day, there’s no way I could get on those cake pops. By the way, you can shoot plush toys into the hoops, if you are game for basketball.

4: Naughty or Nice?

There were two doors split into two colors – naughty for pink and nice for blue. I preferred to enter the nice room, only to find out I’m entering two rooms fused into one, full of candies and candy bars.

There was a jump rope on the nice corner…

3: Cotton Candy

Cotton candies in the form of clouds or trees enveloped the whole room.

The nice part of which is that the treat is cotton candy – the only treat I devoured.

2: Ice Cream Room

What else can we see in an ice cream room but balls full of different colors?

You can also strike a pose inside a giant ice cream cone.

1: Marshmallow Room

Like snow flakes dropping from the sky, this room is filled with marshmallow droppings not from the sky but from the ceiling.

You can read details about marshmallows on murals painted on the wall.

The best part is that you can avail of marshmallow treat, you can either dip it into strawberry or chocolate syrup…yummy!

So there you have it, my very own top eight rundown of rooms inside The Dessert Museum.

Certainly, two hours is not enough to linger inside the themed rooms. My family had a lot of fun and I know that we made the most out of this visit. But if you want to experience going to this place, you mustn’t expect too much in the treats they would provide because it won’t satisfy your sweet tooth cravings. Have in mind that, you want to see this place because of photo ops, something you can post on social media and the most important of all is to have fun with family or friends.

The Dessert Museum

G/F S’ Maison, Condrad Hotel Manila, Mall of Asia Complex, Pasay City Opens from 10:00am to 10:00 pm Online Tickets : Php 699.00 Walk-in Tickets: Php 799.00 Website: http://www.thedessertmuseum.com

Things to ponder:

Make sure that you charge your digital cameras or camera phones.

Dress up! Flaunt your very own OOTD on your visit.

Be courteous enough to wait for your turn.

Have fun with family and friends.

It has been a sweet Sunday for us.

Kath
